issues.title: Z51 Performance Package Differential Overheating
issues.description: The electronic limited-slip differential (eLSD) in Z51 equipped Grand Sports can overheat during aggressive track use, causing the system to shut down and enter limp mode
issues.fix_description: Install aftermarket differential cooler or upgrade to heavy-duty differential fluid
issues.prevention: Allow cool-down periods during track sessions and consider differential cooling modifications

issues.title: Carbon Fiber Hood Delamination
issues.description: The carbon fiber hood on Grand Sport models can experience delamination of the clear coat and carbon fiber layers, particularly around edges and high-stress areas
symptoms: Visible separation of carbon fiber layers
issues.fix_description: Hood replacement under warranty if within coverage period, otherwise professional carbon fiber repair
issues.prevention: Avoid excessive heat exposure and use UV protection when parking outdoors

issues.title: Air Conditioning Compressor Failure
issues.description: Premature A/C compressor failure, particularly in 2017 models, causing complete loss of air conditioning
issues.fix_description: Replace A/C compressor and receiver/dryer, evacuate and recharge system
issues.prevention: Regular A/C system maintenance and use system year-round to keep seals lubricated

issues.title: Carbon Ceramic Brake Squealing
issues.description: Carbon ceramic brakes (optional equipment) produce excessive squealing noise during normal braking, particularly when cold
symptoms: Noise most prominent when brakes are cold
issues.fix_description: Brake pad replacement with updated compound or brake system cleaning
issues.prevention: Normal characteristic of carbon ceramic brakes, bedding procedure may help reduce noise

issues.title: Fuel Tank Evaporative Emission System Leaks
issues.description: EVAP system components including vapor lines and carbon canister can develop leaks, triggering check engine lights
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty EVAP components, most commonly vapor lines or carbon canister
issues.prevention: Avoid overfilling fuel tank and ensure gas cap is properly tightened

issues.title: Transmission Fluid Temperature Issues
issues.description: 8L90 automatic transmission can run hot during aggressive driving, potentially causing premature fluid degradation and shifting issues
issues.fix_description: Transmission fluid change with updated fluid, possible transmission cooler upgrade
issues.prevention: Allow transmission to warm up before aggressive driving and consider aftermarket cooling

issues.title: Door Handle Paint Peeling
issues.description: Black door handles on darker colored Grand Sports experience paint peeling and chipping, exposing plastic underneath
symptoms: Visible paint chips on door handles
issues.fix_description: Sand, prime, and repaint door handles or replace with new painted handles
issues.prevention: Regular cleaning and waxing of door handles, avoid harsh chemicals

issues.title: Engine Oil Consumption
issues.description: LT1 engine may consume oil at higher than normal rates, particularly in track-driven vehicles
symptoms: Need to add oil between changes
issues.fix_description: Monitor oil consumption, possible PCV system service or engine rebuild in severe cases
issues.prevention: Regular oil level monitoring, use recommended oil grade, avoid extended high RPM operation

issues.title: Magnetic Ride Control Sensor Failure
issues.description: Magnetic ride control position sensors can fail, causing the suspension to default to firm mode and lose adaptive capabilities
issues.fix_description: Replace failed position sensors and recalibrate magnetic ride control system
issues.prevention: Avoid harsh impacts and maintain proper ride height

issues.title: Rear Spoiler Adjustment Issues
issues.description: Rear spoiler adjustment mechanism can bind or fail, preventing proper angle adjustment for aerodynamic optimization
issues.fix_description: Clean and lubricate adjustment mechanism or replace spoiler assembly
issues.prevention: Regular cleaning of spoiler mechanism and avoid forcing adjustments

editorial.tagline: Z06 soul with Z51 accessibility and precision
editorial.hero_blurb: The C7 Grand Sport represents Chevrolet's pursuit of the perfect balance between everyday usability and track-focused capability. Born from the legendary Z06's aerodynamic lessons and the base Corvette's approachable character, it delivers supercar performance without the supercar compromises.
editorial.essence: The Grand Sport captures the essence of what made the original 1963 Grand Sport legendary - pure, uncompromising performance wrapped in accessible packaging. It's the thinking enthusiast's Corvette, offering Z06-derived aerodynamics and chassis tuning with naturally aspirated reliability and daily drivability.
editorial.heritage: Named after Zora Arkus-Duntov's original 1963 Grand Sport racers, the C7 Grand Sport revives a nameplate that represents Corvette's racing DNA. The original five Grand Sports were lightweight competition machines that dominated racetracks, and this modern interpretation carries that spirit forward with advanced aerodynamics and suspension technology borrowed from the track-focused Z06.
editorial.design_philosophy: Chevrolet's designers sought to create the ultimate naturally aspirated Corvette experience by combining the Z06's aggressive aerodynamic package with the base car's proven 6.2L LT1 engine. The philosophy centered on maximum track capability without forced induction complexity, delivering pure, linear power delivery in a package that rewards skill development.
editorial.motorsport_history: While the C7 Grand Sport itself didn't compete professionally, it inherited aerodynamic developments from the Z06's racing programs and carries the DNA of the original 1963 Grand Sport racers that competed against Shelby Cobras and Ferrari GTOs. Its wide-body design and advanced cooling systems reflect lessons learned from Corvette Racing's success in IMSA and Le Mans competition.
editorial.engine_character: The naturally aspirated 6.2L LT1 V8 delivers power with surgical precision and intoxicating linearity. Unlike turbocharged engines, it responds instantly to throttle inputs with a crescendo that builds from 1,000 RPM to its 6,600 RPM redline. The engine feels eager and alive, with a character that rewards high-RPM exploration and precise throttle control.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 7-speed manual offers precise, mechanical engagement with perfectly spaced ratios that complement the engine's power band. The 8-speed automatic provides lightning-quick shifts in Track mode while remaining smooth in daily driving. Both transmissions deliver that direct, connected feeling that makes the Grand Sport feel like an extension of the driver's intentions.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The Grand Sport's chassis strikes an extraordinary balance between compliance and control. The Magnetic Ride Control suspension adapts from comfortable cruising to track-ready precision instantly, while the wider Z06-derived rubber and suspension geometry deliver cornering grip that approaches supercar territory without punishing ride quality.
editorial.steering_feel: The electric power steering provides exceptional feedback and linearity, communicating road surface changes and front tire grip levels with remarkable clarity. Weighting is perfectly calibrated - light enough for parking maneuvers yet building appropriate heft as speeds increase, creating confidence-inspiring communication between driver and road.
editorial.brake_confidence: The Brembo brake package delivers fade-resistant stopping power with excellent pedal feel and modulation. The brakes bite progressively and predictably, allowing precise control whether trail-braking into corners or making emergency stops. Cooling is excellent, maintaining consistent performance even during extended track sessions.
editorial.sound_signature: The LT1 produces a deep, melodious rumble at idle that transforms into an intoxicating roar under acceleration. The exhaust note has layers - a muscular bass foundation with higher-frequency harmonics that sing as RPMs climb. In Track mode with exhaust valves open, it delivers one of the most stirring naturally aspirated V8 soundtracks available.
editorial.ideal_owner: Perfect for driving enthusiasts who want maximum Corvette capability without supercharged complexity, track day participants who value reliability over ultimate lap times, and collectors who appreciate the Grand Sport's unique position as the most balanced C7 variant.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Those seeking maximum straight-line acceleration should consider the Z06, while buyers prioritizing comfort over performance would be better served by the base Stingray. It's also not ideal for those who rarely drive spiritedly, as its capabilities deserve to be explored.
editorial.buyers_summary: The C7 Grand Sport represents peak naturally aspirated Corvette evolution, offering 90% of the Z06's capability with greater reliability and daily usability. Focus on finding examples with the Z07 package for ultimate track capability, and prioritize maintenance records over absolute lowest mileage.

expertReviews.verdict: The 2026 Corvette Grand Sport hits the sweet spot in the Corvette lineup, offering Z06-inspired performance and styling with Stingray practicality. With 500hp, excellent handling balance, and everyday usability, it delivers supercar performance at a reasonable price. Perfect for enthusiasts wanting a well-rounded performance machine that's equally at home on track days and daily driving.

expertReviews.verdict: The 2018 C7 Grand Sport represents the best overall Corvette package before the C8, offering Z06 styling and excellent performance from the 460hp LT1 V8 at a more accessible price point. While the reviewer prefers a manual transmission, the automatic is suitable for daily driving. The interior quality is a major improvement over previous generations, and the car delivers excellent sports car performance with surprising comfort.

expertReviews.title: It's HOW good? 2019 Corvette Grand Sport - FULL REVIEW
pros: Rock solid platform with no rattles or shakes
Excellent build quality compared to previous generations
Removable Targa roof that's easy to operate

cons: Displacement on demand system causes annoying shuddering
Analog gauges become pointless with digital displays

expertReviews.verdict: The C7 Grand Sport is praised as the best real-world Corvette, combining track capability with daily usability. The last front-engine Corvette offers excellent build quality, a removable roof, and dry sump oiling. The reviewer's only major complaint is the displacement on demand system, which can be disabled with an aftermarket device. It's described as 'almost a perfect car' for enthusiasts.

expertReviews.title: C7 Corvette Grand Sport Review + Drive!
pros: Fantastic throttle response and torque delivery

Impressive braking performance with massive 6-piston front calipers

expertReviews.verdict: The reviewer is extremely impressed with the C7 Grand Sport, calling it 'perfect' multiple times and stating 'everything is just perfect.' The car demonstrates exceptional handling, braking, and performance with 460 hp from the LT1 V8. The reviewer particularly loves how the car 'fits like a glove' and feels like 'a driver's car 100%' with perfect ergonomics. Despite being 6'5", he fits comfortably. The Grand Sport offers the best balance of power, handling, and brakes in the C7 lineup. The reviewer is so impressed he states he's 'literally obligated to get one' and considers it superior to the C8 in looks.

expertReviews.title: The Perfect Corvette? Driving the C7 Grand Sport Featuring ... by Curious Cars
pros: Perfect balance between base Stingray and extreme ZO6
460 horsepower naturally aspirated V8 engine with great sound
Magnetic dampening suspension system works fantastically well
ZO6 suspension components with more manageable power
Multiple drive mode settings with significant differences
More usable trunk space than previous Corvettes
Can use convertible top up to 30 mph
cons: Overly convoluted exterior styling with too many aerodynamic add-ons
Expensive at $94,000 window sticker price
Carbon ceramic brakes cost $8,000 as standalone option
Convertible with automatic transmission less track-focused
Interior design somewhat convoluted with multiple colors and textures
Seven-speed manual seems excessive
expertReviews.verdict: The C7 Grand Sport perfectly splits the difference between the base Stingray and the extreme ZO6, offering ZO6 handling components with more manageable 460hp. While the styling is overly complex and the $94k price seems high, it delivers the essence of American muscle with sophisticated magnetic suspension. The reviewer prefers it as a coupe with manual transmission for track use, but acknowledges it works well as a convertible grand tourer.
